>What is Api gateways

  >>An API Gateway is like a single entry point for all client requests to your backend services.
  Instead of clients directly calling multiple microservices, they send requests to the API Gateway, and it handles everything behind the scenes.
  Api server does is...
  Request routing

Authentication & authorization ,Load balancing,Rate limiting, Request/response transformation,API aggregation,Logging & monitoring,Caching,SSL termination,Protocol translation.


>What is Gateway Api

  >>Gateway API (Kubernetes)
  Gateway API is a Kubernetes standard used to manage network traffic routing into and within a cluster.
  Gateway API is a Kubernetes resource model for defining how external traffic enters and is routed inside a cluster.
  Gateway API is a collection of Kubernetes API resources used for managing traffic routing and networking in a cluster.
  It provides advanced traffic routing + infrastructure provisioning
  It is an extensible, role-oriented, and protocol-aware system
  
>What is the difference between Api gateway and Gateway APi

  >>The main difference between API Gateway and Gateway API is that API Gateway is an actual running service that processes and forwards requests, 
  whereas Gateway API is a Kubernetes configuration model used to define how traffic routing should be handled. API Gateway works in general microservices architectures, 
  while Gateway API is specifically designed for Kubernetes environments.
  API Gateway Workflow
Client sends request to API Gateway
API Gateway receives the request
Performs authentication and security checks
Applies rate limiting / logging if needed
Routes request to the appropriate microservice
Microservice processes the request
Response is sent back to API Gateway
API Gateway may modify/aggregate response
Final response is sent to the client

🔹 Gateway API Workflow (Kubernetes)
Define GatewayClass, Gateway, and Routes (HTTPRoute) in Kubernetes
Gateway controller (like HAProxy/NGINX) reads these configurations
Client sends request to the Gateway
Gateway receives the request
Gateway checks Route rules
Routes request to the correct Kubernetes Service
Service forwards request to the Pod
Pod processes the request
Response flows back → Gateway → Client
  
>What is HTTP route
  >>HTTPRoute is a Kubernetes Gateway API resource that defines how HTTP/HTTPS traffic should be routed to backend services.
  HTTPRoute mainly specifies:
Path-based routing (e.g., /api, /login)
Header-based routing
Which service to forward traffic to
  >>HTTPRoute defines routing rules for HTTP traffic in Kubernetes Gateway API.
  
